<section xml:id="section-inprod-orthog-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p>
The following definitions concern vectors in an inner product space.
For these definitions, there is no need to distinguish between real and complex inner product spaces.
</p>

<p><dl>

	<li xml:id="definition-inprod-orthog">
	<title><term>orthogonal vectors</term></title>
	<idx><h>orthogonal</h><h>vectors (in an inner product space)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>orthogonal (in an inner product space)</h></idx>
	<p>a pair of vectors whose inner product evaluates to <m>0</m></p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>orthogonal complement (of a subspace <m>U</m>)</term></title>
	<idx><h>orthogonal</h><h>complement</h></idx>
	<idx><h>complement</h><h>orthogonal</h></idx>
	<p> the collection of all vectors in the inner product space that are orthogonal to every vector in <m>U</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><m>\orthogcmp{U}</m></title>
	<p>the orthogonal complement of <m>U</m></p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>orthogonal set of vectors</term></title>
	<idx><h>orthogonal</h><h>set</h></idx>
	<p>a set of vectors in which each vector is orthogonal to each of the other vectors</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>orthonormal set of vectors</term></title>
	<idx><h>orthonormal set</h></idx>
	<p>an orthogonal set of vectors in which each vector is also a unit vector</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>



</section>
